Measurements Near the Interaction Barrier.

x4freetext: The Efficiency Up to 3.3 MeV was Obtained by Means of
Calibrated Sources. It was Extended Up to 10.76 MeV by
Means of the Al-27(P,GAMMA)Si-28 Resonance.
The Detector was Positioned at Zero Degree with Respect
To the Beam Direction at a Distance of About 1 Cm
From the Target.
B-10 Target, Enrichment 96.2%, Thickness
6-10 Microgram/Cm**2. The Boron was Deposited onto
Spectroscopically Pure Copper Discs 0.25 mm Thick.
The B-10 Content in the Copper-Backed Target was
Determined by Measuring Both Elastic Scattering of
Protons and Gamma-Rays Arising from Coulomb Excitation
Of the First Excited State of B-10 Following
Bombardment  with N-14 and 0-16 Ions.
Both Methods Agreed to Within 5%.
Gamma Rays were Observed from Residual Nuclei Formed
By Particle Evaporation from the Compound System.
To Determine the Energy Loss of N-14 Ions in the
Targets, Energy-Loss Thicknesses of Targets were
Deduced by Profiling the Hydrogen Contamination in
The Layers with the H-1(F-19,ALPHA-GAMMA)0-16 Reaction.
Energy-Loss Thicknesses For F-19 Ions were Converted
To Thicknesses For Other Ions Using Stopping-Power
Tables of Northcliffe and Schilling (NUCL.DATA TABLES,
For Cross Section Determination Isotropic Gamma-Ray
Emission was Assumed. Photopeak  Efficiencies and
Gamma-Ray Branchings were Taken Into Account. In Cases
Where More Than One Gamma-Ray was Observed For the
Same Residual Nucleus, Cross Sections were Calculated
From the Intensities of Each of the Gamma-Rays and
The Results were Averaged. Exclusively Transitions
To the Ground-State were Analyzed.
The Probability For Emission of a Particular Gamma-Ray
After Formation of the Respective Residual Nucleus was
Determined from Tabulated Branching Ratios, Calculated
Total Detection Efficiencies, and Relative Populations
Of the Final States. These were Obtained from Different
Theoretical Models and Proved to be Nearly Independent
From the Model Used.
The Numerical Values For these Emission Probabilities
Are Quoted in the Original Paper. They Refer Only to
This Specific Experiment and, Thus, are not Repeated
Here (COMMENT BY THE COMPILER).
The Given Projectile Energy is Equal to the Incident
Energy Minus One-Half the Energy Loss in the Boron
Layer, As Deduced from the F-19 Profiling Results
(SEE UNDER METHOD).
The Overall Systematic Uncertainty of Cross Sections
Resulted from the Quadratic Sum of 5% Each
Uncertainty in Beam Current Integration, Target B-10
Content, and Photopeak Detection Efficiency, with
10% Uncertainties in the Gamma-Ray Emission
Probability Values.
The Uncertainty of the Beam Energy was 0.1%.
Elastic Scattering Differential Cross Sections were
Measured and Analyzed Within the Frame-Work of the
Incoming-Wave Boundary Condition Model. (N-14 + B-10)
Fusion Cross Section was Deduced from the Measured
Total Cross Sections For the Evaporation Residues.
Besides the Measured Cross Sections For Individual
Residues a Calculated Probability For Residues Formed
By 3-Particle Emission was Taken Into Account.
